[02:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. Also this week, this is one of the most powerful image to 3D generators we have so far. It\'s called Pixel3D and this can take a single image and turn it into a 3D model with super'

[03:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'accurate geometry and realistic texture. So here are some examples for your reference. If we take this image of a pizza, here is the 3D reconstruction of this pizza. Notice how accurate this is.'

[03:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And if you compare this with other competitors like Huang Nian 3D, it\'s not even close. This new Pixel3D is just way more accurate and detailed. Here are some examples comparing Pixel3D to'

[03:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'another competitor called Trellis 2. And again, Pixel3D is just a lot better and more accurate. And it\'s able to do so because it tries to generate 3D models in a pixel aligned way. Basically,'

[03:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'instead of loosely giving the model an image and hoping it understands which pixels belong in the 3D space, Pixel3D explicitly connects the 2D pixels in the image with the 3D structure. So, the'

[03:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'output is a really high fidelity 3D mesh with all the details from the original image. So, if you want to generate 3D models like for games or virtual production or product visualization,'

[04:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this is currently the best and most accurate 3D model generator you can use. The awesome thing is they\'ve released this already. So, if you click on this code button and you scroll down a bit, here it contains all the instructions on'

[04:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'how to download and run this locally on your computer. Notice the total size of all these models are 24 GB in size. So, you\'ll need a mid to high-end GPU to run this. If you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in'

[04:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the description below. Next up, this image model is super interesting. It\'s called asymmetric flow models and this is basically an image generator that can make images directly in the pixel space.'

[04:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You see, how traditional image models work is it generates the image in what is called latent space. In theory, this is supposed to save compute and make it simpler. And then after it generates the'

[04:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'image in that latent space, then it uses something called a VAE to convert it back into pixel space which you and I can see. But here, what they did is they completely bypassed this latent space and the need for a VAE. This just'

[05:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generates images directly in pixel space which you and I can see. And the advantage of working directly in pixel space instead of using the compressed latent space is that you can generate hyperrealistic images with sharper'

[05:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'textures and better visual fidelity. If you compare it to just the base model that uses latent space plus another leading competitor when image, you can see that the two traditional methods'

[05:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'look way more plastic and fake, whereas this new method looks a lot more realistic. Or here\'s another example for your reference. Again, this new method seems to look more photorealistic with sharper details and and'

[05:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, the disadvantage of generating this in pixel space, at least previously, is that this takes up way more time and compute. But, from some clever architecture tweaks, they were able to'

[05:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'make this 40% faster. So, compute and speed isn\'t really the bottleneck anymore. And if you compare the performance of this new A Sim flow model against other competitor models that use latent space instead of pixel space,'

[06:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'notice that in terms of image quality, this new one is on average the best. This might represent a paradigm shift in how future image models are designed. The awesome thing is they\'ve released'

