[08:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'down a bit, here it contains all the instructions on how to download and run this locally on your computer. Plus, they also released the script on how you can train and fine-tune this. If you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link'

[08:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to this main page in the description below. Also this week, we have a new AI called Phi Motion, which is pretty useful. This is trying to fix one of the weirdest problem in AI video right now. So, for most video generators,'

[09:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'especially for anatomically tricky movements like figure skating or doing yoga or kung fu, you can see that most video models fail to generate the movements correctly. Sometimes, you get extra limbs. Sometimes, you get missing'

[09:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'limbs. Everything is just deformed and messed up. Well, Phi Motion is basically a new reward system to fix this. In simple terms, it asks, "Could this motion actually happen in the real world?" The way it works is pretty'

[09:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clever. It takes the generated video and recovers a 3D human body from it and then replaces that body in a physics simulator called Mujoco. From there, it scores the movement. For example, are the joints moving in a believable way?'

[09:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Are the feet and body making proper contact with the ground? And does the motion make sense? And it rewards the model for movement that\'s physically correct. So, after applying this new Phi motion to the video generators using the'

[09:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'same prompt, you can see that everything is a lot more anatomically correct. There are still some subtle errors with the generations. It\'s not perfect, but it does fix a lot of these anatomy issues. Now, they released the code to'

[10:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this already. So, if you click on this code button and you scroll down a bit, here it contains the instructions on how to download and set this up on your computer. If you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main'

[10:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'page in the description below. Also this week, Thinking Machines introduces what they call interaction models. These are real-time models that continuously take in audio, video, and text while also thinking and responding and acting at'

[10:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the same time. You see, currently when you talk to a real-time AI voice, it\'s kind of like texting it. You still have to take turns. But, that\'s not how humans collaborate in real life, right? We interrupt and pause and react to'

[10:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'things in real time. So, these interaction models try to take a similar approach. It feels closer to actually collaborating with an AI instead of taking turns. It can notice silence, overlapping speech, interruptions, and'

[11:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'visual cues as part of the actual conversation. Here are some examples. I heard mountain biking is a lot of fun, so I wanted to go mountain bike. And I was thinking to actually take my'

[11:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'parents with me. They\'re pretty old. They\'re 70, almost 80, but I thought that would be a fun trip together. &gt;&gt; Wait, no. Don\'t take them mountain biking at 80. That\'s incredibly risky. They could easily get seriously hurt. Pick something safer. Hmm. I think'

[11:29] [scene:talk]
